lexUnit.name: guess.v
lexUnit.definition: COD: estimate or suppose (something) without sufficient information to be sure of being correct.

sentence.text: Pascoe did n't ask about the people , but he guessed that they had grown angry waiting for the debt to be paid .
Trent guessed that she was awake .
Brenda guessed that it was a big responsibility for him and was determined not to let him down .
Duncan had guessed right about it being a Shogun , the smaller , two-door version .
He had guessed correctly .
Dexter guessed immediately that the man was trying to extract an exclusive story on the investigation into the murder of Nicola Sharpe .
Just guess who 's come to pay you a little visit ! "
It is easy enough to guess when these parishes were enclosed .
He guessed that when they made their report , probably by radio to a close in-surface unit , the MOD would finish the job and order the destruction of the Titron .

Lewis immediately guessed that this suggestion came not from Chavasse but from his Aunt Lily , and in the irrational way that such family meddling irritates , this prompted an extraordinary flow of anger .
I could immediately guess why she was not too keen to stay .
Somehow she 'd already guessed the other woman 's identity .
` If they all lived , guess how many rats there 'd be in this country in five years .
However , as will be evident , we are really still guessing as to the true cause of ice ages .
But Sir Patrick certainly never guessed what was to come .
I expect you 've guessed by now I 'm a dog .
You must have guessed by now that 1-2-3 for Windows is n't the best Windows spreadsheet on the market .
I wondered if he guessed that I had by now even worse fears about Bobbie .
And I guess most of the people in this audience today would think of water being supplied by water boards .
I guess spiritual is the right word . "
She guessed these were harlots who were prepared to entertain the men according to their preferences .
I guess there are lesbian cats ? "
